When this rule is mentioned use this documentation:

# Annotations

It is possible to add annotations in the fields attaching metadata to the Types definitions.
The supported annotations are: Label, Description, and SemanticTerms. These are all defined in
the [com::mulesoft::connectivity::decorator::Annotations](mdc:../../connectivity-language/src/main/dw/com/mulesoft/connectivity/decorator/Annotations.dwl)
module.

These annotations add metadata in a similar way to the `<~` operator in DataWeave (the `<~` operator _replaces_ while
these annotations _add_). There's an additionally supported kind of metadata-annotated information and that is `format`.
The list of supported formatted types is available at the [com::mulesoft::connectivity::Types](mdc:../../connectivity-language/src/main/dw/com/mulesoft/connectivity/Types.dwl) module.

## Label

Add a label annotation in a Type like this:
```
type CreateTicketType = {
    projectId: @Label(value = "Project ID") String,
    ticketType: String,
}
```

## Description

Add a description annotation in a Type like this:
```
type CreateTicketType = {
    projectId: String,
    ticketType: @Description(value = "The Type of the project to be created") String,
}
```

## Format

The supported Format annotations are: "date" and "date-time" for Strings,
and "integer", "float", "double", "int32" and "int64" for Numbers.
Instead of using a format metadata annotation (like `String <~ { format: "date-time" }`) use the equivalent formatted
type defined in the `Types` module (like `LWDateTime`)

An example request structure using formatted types follows:
```
type CreateTicketType = {
    projectId: String,
    ticketType: String,
    ticketDate: LWDate,
    createdAt: LWDateTime,
    amount: Integer,
    size: Float,
    price: Double,
    count: Int32,
    total: Int64
}
```

## Semantic Terms

If using the existing Auth Schemas defined in [Http.dwl](mdc:https:/github.com/mulesoft/interpreted-connectivity-link-weave/blob/develop/connectivity-language/src/main/dw/com/mulesoft/connectivity/transport/Http.dwl) the fields will have the corresponding annotations,
you won't have to declare it. If using a custom Type, you will have to add the semanticTerms annotations.
Look at [connections](mdc:connections.md) for more info.
```
type BasicAuthSchema = {
    username: @SemanticTerms(value = ["username"]) String,
    password: @SemanticTerms(value = ["password"]) String
}

type BearerAuthSchema = {
    token: @SemanticTerms(value = ["secretToken"]) String
}

type ApiKeyAuthSchema = {|
    apiKey: @SemanticTerms(value = ["apiKey"]) String
|}

type OAuth2AuthSchema = {|
    accessToken: @SemanticTerms(value = ["password"]) String
|}
